This way, the original `foo` is not directly called from outside of this class anymore and it's clear that you are using a different method name. But remember to use meaningful names for your methods in order maintainability when refactoring or updating code later on! 
Also note: The switch statement will only execute one case, so if the condition inside `if` is not met then no break would be executed and execution continues into next cases until it encounters a 'break' command. If you want to make sure all conditions are covered in your method body (i.e., there should never reach here), use multiple switch statements or fallthroughs instead of if-else chains inside the case block, as shown below:
```java 
public class Example {  
    public void fancyFoo(int i) { // renamed function to avoid naming conflict with foo.
        switch (i){    
            case 1 :     
                System.out.println("Case one");       break;        
           default:         
               if (!true ){   /* add your condition here */}    return ;//break out of all cases, no further execution in this block is allowed unless you have a fallthrough statement below it  //additional code to be executed when none above conditions are met.     break;      }        case ... :
```         In the example given before `fancyFoo` method will not execute if condition inside 'if' isn’t satisfied, and no further execution in this block is allowed unless you have a fallthrough statement below it or use multiple switch cases as shown above.  If none of these conditions are met then default case (i.e., the last `case : ...`) will be executed if there aren't any break statements before them, and no further execution in this block is allowed unless you have a fallthrough statement below it or use multiple switch cases as shown above with different condition inside 'if'.

